extends /views/templates/layouts/_base

append variables
	- pagetitle = "Deep linking"

block content
	.lane
		.container
			.page-header
				h1 Deep linking
				p.lead Link directly to any panel state.

	+section("How it works")
		p Both components determine the initial state on every page load from three sources, checked in order:
		.card
			ol
				li #[strong URL param] (#[code ?panel=]): Reading of the URL parameter will always be done, no config needed. See below.
				li #[strong localStorage]: used when #[code persist] is enabled and no URL param applied. See #[a(href=url('/sharedconcepts/persisting.html')) Persisting state].
				li #[strong HTML default]: the markup state like #[code class="active"] panel (PanelSet) or #[code class="is-open"] (Panel / closable PanelSet).

		p On this page we delve a bit deeper into #[strong deep linking]. 


	+section("Reading the URL parameter")
		p #[strong Reading is always on.] Panel and PanelSet always check the #[code ?panel=] param on load. Any link with #[code ?panel=id] opens that panel. For example, a link like #[a(href=url('/index.html?panel=demo-panel-4')) index.html?panel=demo-panel-4] opens the panel with ID #[code demo-panel-4] on page load. Note that we do not use just a hash, because that is much more limited. The #[code ?panel=] param is designed to be purely for panel state.


		p The #[code ?panel=] query param is a comma-separated list of panel IDs.

		+codeblock('HTML').
			<!-- Open or activate a single panel -->
			<a href="?panel=pricing">Link to Pricing</a>

			<!-- Open or activate multiple panels at once -->
			<a href="?panel=pricing,sidebar">Pricing tab open, sidebar open</a>


		p Because HTML IDs are (or at least should be) unique per HTML page, a panel ID always points to exactly one element, whether it is a standalone #[code [data-panel]] collapse or a #[code [role="tabpanel"]] inside a PanelSet.



	+section("Writing the URL parameter")

		p #[strong Writing is optional.] By default the URL is never modified. 
		
		p However, you can enable #[code deepLink] to keep the URL in sync as the user opens and closes panels, so the current state can be shared from the address bar. When any panel (Panel or PanelSet) opens, its ID is added to #[code ?panel=]. When it closes, the ID is removed. Multiple open panels accumulate naturally: #[code ?panel=faq-1,faq-2].

		.card
			.grid-2

				div
					h3 Deep linking in Panel
					.demo
						button(aria-controls="paneldl" aria-expanded="false") Toggle panel

						div#paneldl(data-panel data-panel-deeplink)
							.panel-wrapper
								h3= example1Title
								+example-1-content

					div.bottom.column.gap-1
						+codeblock('JavaScript').
							new Panel('#sidebar', { deepLink: true });
							// or via init
							Panel.init({ deepLink: true });

						+codeblock('HTML')
							#sidebar(data-panel data-panel-deeplink) ...





				div
					h3 Deep linking in PanelSet
					.demo
						+exampletabset('panelsetdl')
						+examplepanelset('panelsetdl')(data-panel-deeplink)

					div.bottom.column.gap-1
						+codeblock('JavaScript').
							new PanelSet('#example', { deepLink: true });
							// or via init
							PanelSet.init({ deepLink: true });

						+codeblock('HTML')
							#example(data-panelset data-panel-deeplink) ...

						p Note: a PanelSet uses #[code data-panel-deeplink] (the #[code panel-] prefix), not #[code data-panelset-deeplink]. The deep-link attributes are shared with Panel, so the prefix stays #[code panel-] on both.


			p Play around with the two examples above, and reload the page. Both come back in the same state you left them. You can also send the link to a friend and the same panels will be opened.

		p For accordion groups, set #[code data-panel-deeplink] on the #[code [data-panel-group]] element to cover all panels in the group at once.



	+section("Suppressing transitions on load")
		p When a panel opens from a URL parameter, it snaps open instantly without an animation. Any CSS transitions on the surrounding elements (such as a chevron rotation or a border color change) would still play, which can look wrong on a cold page load.

		p Panel adds an #[code is-restored] class to the element for exactly one paint cycle when this happens. You can use it to suppress those transitions:

		+codeblock('CSS').
			:has(> [data-panel].is-restored),
			:has(> [data-panel].is-restored) * {
				transition: none !important;
			}

		p The direct-child combinator (#[code >]) keeps the selector scoped to the immediate parent of the panel, so only that container and its contents are affected. The class is removed after the first paint, so all subsequent opens and closes animate normally.

	+section("Mixed components")
		p Because the param is a flat list of IDs, PanelSet panels and standalone panels can coexist in the same URL without any special syntax.

		+codeblock('HTML').
			<!-- Activate the Pricing tab and open the sidebar in one link -->
			<a href="?panel=pricing,sidebar">View pricing with sidebar open</a>

append styles
	style.
		[data-panelset-trackheight] {
			height: var(--ps-max-height);
		}

append scripts
	if isProd
		script(src=`${basePath}assets/scripts/example.js` vite-ignore)
		script(src=`${basePath}lib/panelset.js` vite-ignore)
		script.
			Panel.init();
			PanelSet.init();
	else
		script(type="module" src="/src/assets/scripts/example.js")
		script(type="module").
			import { PanelSet, Panel } from 'panelset';
			Panel.init({ debug: true });
			PanelSet.init({ debug: true });
